- t13 ‘Reality Has a Well-Known Liberal Bias’:1 The End(s) of Satire in Trump’s America -- t14 Spectacle of Decency: Repairing America after Trump -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores the cultural and political significance of the election of President TrumpExplores Trump in an intellectually robust way, linking his election and presidency to broader themes of American political history and cultureExamines the disruption to the American political system and shifting conceptions of the American national identity in the wake of Trump’s electionIlluminates the convergence of political life and entertainment in the Trump era, and the ways in which the American public sphere is being radically reconfigured by new and social media to polarise American political discourseFeatures contributions from a truly international range of scholars and professionals working in political journalismDonald J. Trump’s presidency has delivered a seismic shock to the American political system, its public sphere, and to our political culture worldwide. Written by leading scholars across a range of disciplines, as well as professionals in the field of political journalism, this collection of essays offers a deeper understanding of Trump and the impact that his rise to power has had both domestically and worldwide.The first section provides varied perspectives on the realignments of political culture in the United States that signify a paradigm shift, a radical disruption of fundamental beliefs and values about the political process and national identity. The second section of the book focuses on US foreign policy and diplomacy, taking stock of how the Trump presidency has disturbed the international system and US primacy within it. The third section of the book addresses the dynamics and consequences of what has come to be called post-truth" politics, where conviction surpasses facts and the norms of political communication have been profoundly disrupted. "  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aCarroll, Hamilton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeckman, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGardner, Kelley M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHajihosseini, Alireza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelleter, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLilli, Eugenio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLucas, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGreevy, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNegra, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPease, Donald E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRyan, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShapiro, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVon Eschen, Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311078041340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147445889440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474458894423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474458894/original  a978-3-11-078041-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA